  <h2>What Is LED Light Therapy, and Does It Actually Work?</h2>
  <p>
    LED light therapy uses specific wavelengths of light—primarily red (600–700 nm) and near-infrared (700–1100 nm)—to stimulate cellular activity in the skin. The science is real: clinical studies show that red and near-infrared light increases expression of hyaluronic acid synthase and elastin in skin cells, both critical for hydration and firmness.
  </p>

  <p>
    However, there's a gap between what the science shows and what at-home masks deliver. Professional in-office LED treatments use more powerful light intensities than consumer devices. At-home masks are safer but less potent.
  </p>

